title: For Sale:  Please stop calling them "Hi Capacity"
postcontent:
To whom it may concern,

Please stop using the words "Hi Capacity" unless they are true high capacity magazines (i.e. one that the gun was not shipped standard with or the gun was made for)  For instance, a Glock 17 was designed to have a 17 round magazine and a 17 round Glock 17 magazine is not "Hi Cap", it is a standard capacity for the gun.  A Glock 18 magazine for use in a Glock 17 could be described as high capacity or an AR drum that holds more than 30 rounds.

The term "Hi Cap" is a word that the left wants to use for any magazine that holds more than 10 rounds and you are just giving them more power when you start using their made up words such as "Assault Weapon" and "Hi Cap".

Sincerely, 

Concerned Gun Owner

title: For Sale:  Remington built Danish M-1867 rifl
postcontent: Excellent bore which shows little use. Walnut stock/foregrip in great shape, and has just six or seven small dents & pressure dings. Looks to be fired very little. Matching numbers on all components. Stamped Kjobenhavns Toiuus 1883 behind hammer. Includes cleaning rod. According to my research it looks like this rifle was modified by the Danes in later years to accept a second firing pin (for center fire cartridges)when these rifles were issued to their version of the Coast Guard---hence the rather large 3-1/4" tall rear sight. Stock is stamped with number 63666 just ahead of the rear sling mount, and there appears a rectangle stamp on top of the stock with the initials 'G.C.'. Blueing on barrel rates at least an 8, and receiver has a 'case hardened' look that is rather pretty. All in all this is simply a great looking antique rifle with a cool history. And just in time for Valentine's Day
